e.p. <p>"saving the world in style"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ualucard1515.showPublicProfile?language=EN>alucard1515</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator <img src=http://contest.polykarbon.com/badge1.gif></span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/21/02 4:32:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.undeadart.com/forum/alucard.gif width=100 height=94></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Warning Labels for Video Games?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> but i don't think you can say that it has no effect on kids who play it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I can, and do.<br>
<br>
First of all, you said KILLING in the first part, now you're saying fighting. That's not the same thing. Sure, it's still violence, but it's not lifelike, and unless kids have all of a sudden developed the abilities to jump several stories into the air and can toss bombs and projectiles at each other, it's kind of hard to emulate what's going on. I'm sure there are a few morons that will try to copy what they see, but I believe that's the exception to the rule.<br>
<br>
I grew up on violent movies and games and I wasn't violent. I never got into fights, because real life is not a movie, real life is not a game. <br>
<br>
Go ahead, put warning labels on games, I don't see a problem with that. I just don't see why everyone believes that games are going to affect people so incredibly that they'll do some of these crazy things. It's just an easy answer. There is probably not just ONE thing that makes people one way. Have you ever considered that it isn't the violent games that make kids violent? Maybe their violent tendencies make violent television or games more appealing to them? <br>
<br>
And let's not pretend that violence is some kind of new problem that just sprang up out of nowhere. Kids were still fighting and hitting each other way before video games or television.<br>
<br>
Besides, this has very little to do with this guy. He wasn't a little kid, he was an adult living on his own. It wasn't the game that made him the way he was. If he was so alone and depressed and he had no Everquest, he would have found something else to obsess himself with.<br>
<br>
I don't get these arguments anyway. People should stop making games or movies because some kid MIGHT get their hands on it and MIGHT try to emulate something from it? Instead of trying to eliminate the violent movies and games, why not just make it more difficult for it to get into the hands of children? Because I don't like having to live in a child's world. <p><table width=100% border=0>
