</table></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uemmapeel1601.showPublicProfile?language=EN>emmapeel1601</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/21/02 6:39:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Warning Labels for Video Games?</span><hr size=1> the characters do kill each other in super smash brothers. or maybe it's like in Tekken Tag Tournament where they just get KOed. and kids don't usually have access to bombs, ray guns or the like but one of the weapons in Super Smash Bros. is a stick. and throwing rocks is a good way to pretend at throwing bombs. <br>
<br>
that said, i do think you are misinterpreting what i was trying to say. <br>
i know that kids have violent tendencies that are just part of human nature. i am not trying to say that video games turn every kid into a rabid killer, that's hardly the case. all i'm saying is that people who say that video games and movies that depict scenes of violence have no effect on those who play and watch them are deluding themselves. <br>
human nature becomes desensitized to anything they see repeatedly. there were widespread reports in the aftermath of Sept. 11 that children were telling their teachers that they simply couldn't be upset by the collapse of the Twin Towers. it reminded them too much of scenes they had seen in movies like Independence Day for them to be able to grasp what had really happened. <br>
we respond to the environment around us and as violence in games, movies and TV becomes more and more acceptable as a form of entertainment we become less sensitive to it. <br>
that was what i was trying to say before, not that violent games spark the same kind of violence, but they slowly create a spirit of indifference. again, that indifference is nearly imperceptable in most people but it is still there. <br>
<br>
*whew* well, i hope that cleared things up, although i may have just muddied the waters. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
oh, and i realize the guy who was the initial focus of this discussion was an adult. it just seemed that the posts that followed were making the argument that games don't affect anyone. i think that children/young people are actually more susceptible because they don't have &quot;real world&quot; experience that most adults do. <br>
